==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*feþrō'', from Indo-European ''*peta-'' ‘fly’.  Cognate with Old Frisian [[feþere]], Old Saxon [[feþera]] (Dutch [[veder]], [[veer]]), Old High German [[fedara]] (German [[Feder]]), Old Norse [[fjǫðr]] (Swedish [[fjäder]]).  The IE root is also the source of Greek [[πετεσθαι]], [[πτωσις]], Latin [[penna]], Celtic ''*petno-'' (Old Irish [[én]], Breton [[ein]] ‘bird’).

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'feðeɹ/

===Noun===
'''feþer''' ''f''
# a [[feather]]
#:''Se fenix ascæceþ feðre'': the phoenix shakes its feathers.

